<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-22T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-22T08:00:00-05:00" n="687" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d687">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/3710: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hong Kong</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Southard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hong
                                        Kong</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-22T21:00:00+08:00">October 22, 1938—9
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received October 22—5 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Referring to your telegram of October 19, 10 [<hi rend="italic">11</hi>]
                                a.m.<note n="25" xml:id="d687fn25">Not printed.</note> about
                            American-born Chinese on Shameen. I have talked with the British
                            Ambassador who asks me to tell you that he is immediately taking the
                            matter up by telegraph and will help all he can but is not in a position
                            to say what the decision may be.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Chungking, Canton. Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Southard</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>